Class CppHashMap

java.lang.Object
  com.versant.trans.SCO
      com.versant.util.CppHashMap
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
public class CppHashMap
extends SCO
implements java.lang.Cloneable, java.io.Serializable

This is a Second Class Object to be used only as an attribute in a persistent instance of a C++ defined class when you share objects and classes created from the VERSANT C++ language interface with the transparent Java binding.

This class is based on the HashMap class in the java.util package of JDK 1.2

As an object that maps keys to values, a CppHashMap cannot contain duplicate keys. Each key can map to, at the most, only one value.

The CppHashMap provides three views, which allow a CppHashMap's contents to be viewed as a collection of keys, values, or key-value mappings. The order of a CppHashMap is defined as the order in which the iterators on the CppHashMap's views return their elements. There is no guarantee to the order of the returned elements.

The CPPHashMap provides two "standard" constructors:

•    A void (no arguments) constructor which creates an empty CppHashMap.

•    A constructor with a single argument of type CppHashMap, which creates a new CppHashMap with the same key-value mappings as its argument. In effect, the latter constructor allows the user to copy any CppHashMap, producing an equivalent CppHashMap of the desired class.

This implementation provides constant-time performance for the basic operations (get and put), assuming the hash function disperses the elements properly among the buckets. Iteration requires time proportional to the number of buckets in the hash table plus the size of the Map (the number of key-value mappings).

An instance of CppHashMap has two parameters that affect its efficiency: its capacity and its load factor. The load factor should be between 0.0 and 1.0. When the number of entries in the CppHashMap exceeds the product of the load factor and the current capacity, the capacity is increased by calling the rehash() method. Larger load factors use memory more efficiently, at the expense of larger expected time per lookup.

If you make many entries in a CppHashMap, then creating it with a sufficiently large capacity allows the entries to be inserted more efficiently. This approach is preferable to allowing it to perform automatic rehashing as needed to increase the table.

Note that this implementation is not synchronized.

If multiple threads access a CppHashMap concurrently, and at least one of the threads modifies the CppHashMap structurally, it must be synchronized externally. (A structural modification is any operation that adds or deletes one or more mappings; merely changing the value associated with a key that is already contained in the Table is not a structural modification.)

The Iterators returned by the iterator methods of the CppHashMaps returned by all of CppHashMap's view methods are fail-fast: if the CppHashMap is structurally modified at any time after the Iterator is created, except through the Iterator's own remove or add methods, the Iterator throws a RuntimeException. Thus, in the face of concurrent modification, the Iterator fails quickly and cleanly, rather than risking arbitrary, non-deterministic behavior at an undetermined time in the future.
